type of warriorlike individual who can be found existing among the monksThese are the five warriorlike individuals who can be found existing among the monks Paisambhid formed from pai  sa  bhid where pai  sa should probably be understood as back together and the verbal root bhid means to break split severRhys Davids and Stede propose that a literal rendering would be resolving continuous breaking up and gloss this as analysis analytic insight discriminating knowledge moreover they associate it with the idea of logical analysisBhikkhu Nyanatiloka similarly renders the term as analytical knowledge but also as discriminationBhikkhu amoli voices a divergent view in a note to his translation of in Buddhaghosas Visuddhimagga XIV where he renders paisambhid as discriminationIn this translation I have decided to follow amolis rendering of the termEven so discrimination does not so clearly capture the double sense of both taking apart and combining together that seems to be suggested by paisambhidOne kind of epistemological process which involves both of these activities is classification in which various things even within a given class or group are divided and grouped according to their peculiar differences and similarities with respect to one anotherSo while each of the paisambhid is itself a classification of a kind of knowledge it is also possible that each one is also understood to be a kind of ability to classify correctly the elements belonging to the kind of knowledge that falls into its scopeIn Visuddhimagga Buddhaghosa presents a list of what he considers to be twelve different kinds of pa the set of catasso paisambhid four discriminations is the twelfth of theseHe goes on to give an extensive discussion of them which although of interest is very much influenced by the Abhidhamma interpretation of the term Buddhaghosa begins by citing the definition of the Abhidhamma Vibhaga and then proceeds to follow the subsequent Vibhaga discussionIf Buddhaghosa was indeed the author of the Sumagalavilsin then his Abhidhammabased account of the four paisambhid may well diverge from the original meaning of the term in the period in which the Suttas evolved and were committed to memoryFor the same reasons this is very probably also the case for many commentarial interpretations of earlier Sutta conceptsPaibhna understanding illumination intelligence readiness or confidence of speech promptitude witCfthe Sanskrit pratibhna from prati  bh pratibhti to shine upon to appear to the mind to become clear or manifest thus pratibhna becoming clear or visible obviousness intelligence eloquence brilliancy boldness audacityWe might also cite here the definition from Vibhaga with which Buddhaghosa opens his discussion of the four paisambhidKnowledge with respect to meaning is discrimination of meaning knowledge with respect to dhamma is discrimination of dhamma knowledge with respect to the linguistic expression of dhamma is discrimination of language and knowledge with respect to kinds of knowledge is discrimination of paibhnaatthe a atthapaisambhid dhamme a dhammapaisambhid tatra dhammaniruttbhilpe a niruttipaisambhid esu a paibhnapaisambhidamoli in his translation of this passage as cited within Buddhaghosas text renders paibhna as perspicuityYath vimutta citta paccavekkhatiIn the Introduction to the commentary to Dgha Nikya known as the Sumagalavilsin and traditionally attributed to Buddhaghosa there is the following interesting reference to the four discriminationsMoreover a bhikkhu wellpractised in Vinaya depending on the attainment of virtue arrives at the three knowledges wellpractised in Sutta depending on the attainment of concentration he arrives at the six higher knowledges wellpractised in Abhidhamma depending on the attainment of wisdom he arrives at the four discriminationsvinaye pana suppaipanno bhikkhu slasampada nissya tisso vijj pputi sutte suppaipanno samdhisampada nissya cha abhi pputi abhidhamme suppaipanno pasampada nissya catasso paisambhid pputi From this we see that the commentator believed that the four discriminations were the result of mastery of the Abhidhamma and that the Abhidhamma is associated with the development of wisdomHowever given that the attainment of the four paisambidh is mentioned here in this sutta it follows that the paisambidh cannot be a result of a mastery of the Abhidhamma because the Abhidhamma did not even exist at the time of the compilation of the suttasWe know this even according to the traditional evidence from the reports of the First and Second Councils contained in the last two sections of the Cullavagga the second part of the Khandhaka in the Vinaya PiakaIn the report of the First Council therein only the Vinaya and the Dhamma are mentioned Come friends let us chant the Dhamma and the VinayaVenerable Mahkassapa questions Venerable Upli concerning the contexts of the Vinaya and then he questions the Venerable nanda concerning the contexts of the Suttas starting with the Brahmajla then the SmaaphalaIn this way he asked about the five Nikyas questioned consecutively Venerable nanda answeredAgain in the report of the Second Council said in the text itself to have taken place one hundred years after the Buddhas Parinibbna the resolution of the dispute between the two groups of monks depends upon a sound knowledge of the Vinaya and the DhammaThus for example The Venerable Elder has learned much Dhamma and Vinaya at the feet of his spiritual teacherWhen the Venerable Elder is reflecting upon the Dhamma and Vinaya how is it The Venerable Revata to whom this passage refers is earlier described as very learned one to whom the gama has been handed down a bearer of the Dhamma the Vinaya the mtik intelligent accomplished wise modest meticulous anxious to observe the discipline Here the word mtik matrices codes most probably refers to the rules of the Ptimokkhasutta rules for monks and rules for nunsOn this matter see Ovon Hinber A Handbook of Pli Literature  and See also Bhikkhus Bodhi and amoli The Middle Length Discourses of the Buddha p n The Codes are probably the rules of the Ptimokkha abstracted from their explanatory matrix as well as lists of the primary doctrinal categories used for expounding the Dhamma Again see also FWatanabe Philosophy and its Development in the Nikyas and Abhidhamma pThis is clearly the earliest usage and meaning of the word mtik as it is found in the Vinaya and SuttasFrom such indications we may conclude that it was fundamentally anachronistic of the commentator to suppose that the paisambhid were attainments resulting from a mastery of the much later Abhidhamma literature for the latter simply did not exist at the time of the learning compilation and original transmission of the SuttasNow in this present sutta we find very specific reference made to five qualities that is the four paisambidh in conjunction with what we must evidently take to be the fifth quality in question yathvimutta citta paccavekkhati he reflects upon mind as liberatedIt is probable that this fifth quality is the crucial one and that without it the four other qualities would by no means produce the result which is the theme of the sutta ie nacirasseva akuppa paivijjhati in no long time he penetrates and intuits the UnshakeableThen a certain monk went to the Blessed One and on arrival having bowed down to him sat to one sideAs he was sitting there he said to the Blessed One One who dwells in the Dhamma one who dwells in the Dhamma thus it is said lordTo what extent is a bhikkhu one who dwells in the DhammaMonk there is the case where a monk studies the Dhamma dialogues narratives of mixed prose and verse explanations verses spontaneous exclamations quotations birth stories amazing events question  answer sessionsHe spends the day in DhammastudyHe neglects seclusionHe doesnt commit himself to internal tranquillity of awarenessThis is called a monk who is keen on study not one who dwells in the DhammaThen there is the case whe